ng on history, literary studies, ritual studies, Sanskrit philology, narrative studies, and philosophy, Lindquist traces Yājñavalkya’s literary life—from his earliest mentions in ritual texts, through his developing biography in the Upaniṣads, and finally to his role as a hoary sage in narrative literature—offering the first detailed monograph on this central figure in early Indian religious and literary history.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 07. Mrz 2024) 4aAsian Studies : Asian Literature. 4aAsian Studies : India and South Asian Studies. 4aPhilosophy : Philosophy of Religion. 4aReligion and Spirituality : Hindu Studies. 7aRELIGION / Hinduism / History.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUNY Press eBook Package 2023z978311149193640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978143849564440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781438495644423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781438495644/original  a978-3-11-149193-6  SUNY Press eBook Package 2023b2023  aGBV-deGruyter-alles